{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.08,0.83,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72437"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10163"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72437"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin has several mechanisms to protect against harmful effects of ultraviolet radiation from sunlight.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how melanin protects skin cells from ultraviolet radiation damage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produces protective antibodies","Increases skin cell turnover rate","Absorbs and scatters harmful UV radiation","Reduces blood flow to exposed areas","Repairs UV-induced DNA damage"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanin absorbs and scatters harmful UV radiation\u003C/strong\u003E, preventing it from reaching vulnerable cellular structures including DNA. This pigment acts as a natural sunscreen, converting the absorbed UV energy into heat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces protective antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E - Melanin is a pigment molecule and does not have any role in immune system function or antibody production.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases skin cell turnover rate\u003C/strong\u003E - While increased cell turnover can help remove damaged cells, this is not a mechanism by which melanin provides protection against UV radiation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces blood flow to exposed areas\u003C/strong\u003E - UV exposure typically increases rather than decreases blood flow as part of the inflammatory response to damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepairs UV-induced DNA damage\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA repair is carried out by specific enzyme systems such as nucleotide excision repair, not by melanin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe effectiveness of melanin protection varies with skin type, with higher melanin concentrations providing greater UV protection. This explains why darker-skinned individuals have more natural protection against UV damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultraviolet B (UVB) radiation primarily affects the epidermis and causes direct DNA damage and sunburn.","Ultraviolet A (UVA) radiation penetrates more deeply into the dermis and causes photoageing through oxidative stress.","Melanin provides protection against UV damage by absorbing and scattering harmful radiation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:42:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:43:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72437"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Sk